Introduction

Tumors are abnormal growth tissues in the body, and can be classified as either benign or malignant. Benign tumors are not harmful, while malignant tumors are harmful and typically cancerous. There are many different features that can vary between tumors, such as the radius, texture, perimeter, area, and more. Figuring out what feature differs the most between tumors could help doctors catch malignant tumors early, preventing invasive medical procedures like chemotherapy and radiotherapy. In this report, we examine different breast tumors observed in various patients in Wisconsin to see which feature(s) differ the most between those who have breast cancer and those who dont. We examine the different features of these tumors and their respective means and standard deviations over all the samples, with the goal to have an answer to the following questions.

-Which features can be used to identify if the breast tumor is benign or malignant?

Background

This data was collected by UCI to look at the features of different digitized images of a fine needle aspirate (FNA) of a breast mass (tumor). They describe the characteristics of the cell nuclei present in the image and whether the breast mass was malignant (cancerous) or benign (non-cancerous). 10 real-valued features are computed for each cell nucleus: radius, texture, perimeter, area, smoothness, compactness, concavity, concave points, symmetry, and fractal dimension, and we will focus on the first 8 features. The data set also contains an ID number for each case, or breast mass that was studied in Wisconsin. The data set is a CSV file and its size is 32 x 700. It is made available online at their website. Note that specific units were not given in the data set.We will analyze various features of breast tumors to look at the relationship between these features, as well as highlight key differences between malignant and benign tumors. With this analysis, we will be able to better understand how to identify breast cancer in patients.

Variable Descriptions

Key Variables from the Breast Cancer Wisconsin (Diagnostic) Data Set
Name Description
id ID number of the breast tissue
diagnosis the diagnosis of breast tissues (M = malignant, B = benign)
radius_mean mean of distances from center to points on the perimeter
texture_mean standard deviation of gray-scale values
perimeter_mean mean size of the core tumor perimeter
area_mean mean size of the core tumor area
smoothness_mean mean of local variation in radius lengths
compactness_mean mean of perimeter^2 / area - 1.0
concavity_mean mean of severity of concave portions of the contour
concave points_mean mean for number of concave portions of the contour

Discussion

By examining the correlation between perimeter and area, and radius and area, we get positive slopes in both linear modules, and we observe similar trend that fits our expectation that area holds a quadratic relation to radius and perimeter. Through examining the different variables of the dataset through various density plots, we can conclude that basing the probability off the aspects of smoothness and texture of the tumor is inconclusive. All the other variables, specifically area of the tumor shows the most significant discrepancies among tumor diagnosis of patients. This is further highlighted in the 95% confidence intervals for both benign and malignant tumors as there is a massive difference between the endpoints of each confidence interval ((449.6521, 477.5114) for benign tumors and (928.5622, 1028.1906) for benign tumors. This allows us to conclude that looking at the variable of tumor mean area for a given patient is the best sign at predicting the cancer diagnosis of a given patient.

Potential Short Comings

Some possible shortcomings of our analysis come in the exclusion of units in the dataset that was given. I would say we are not missing any key data as there are many variables provided to describe each patients tumor(s) but again it can be difficult to draw concrete conclusion without clear and comparable units provided. This sample may not be the largest size, but where this comes into play more is in the difference between sample size of patients with malignant tumors and those with begin tumors (212 Malignant tumor patients, 356 Benign tumor patients)
